Package: port
Title: Consistency Checks for Reported Rounded Correlation Matrices
Version: 0.1.0
Authors@R:
    person("Ian", "Hussey", email = "ian.hussey@unibe.ch", role = c("aut", "cre"))
Description: Forensic meta-science tools for auditing reported correlation
    matrices. Published correlations are rounded, so each true value lies
    somewhere within a small range around the printed number. The package
    asks whether any valid correlation matrix -- one that is positive
    semidefinite (PSD) -- can lie within all of those ranges at once. When
    none can, the reported table cannot have arisen as a single complete
    set of Pearson correlations; the cause may be benign (for example
    missing values handled pairwise, a mix of correlation types, or
    non-Pearson correlations). Such 'inconsistent' findings rest on a
    rigorous floating-point error bound (Higham (2002)
    <doi:10.1137/1.9780898718027>)
    and so do not depend on the tolerances of a numerical solver. A
    'consistent' finding is confirmed by constructing a valid matrix within
    the ranges and verifying it with a guaranteed Cholesky test (Rump (2006)
    <doi:10.1007/s10543-006-0056-1>). Beyond the verdict, the package points
    to the cells, variables, or triples that drive an inconsistent result,
    grades how far the table is from consistency, and separates benign
    structural causes from substantive errors. A further layer applies the
    same checks to reliability-corrected (disattenuated) correlations.
URL: https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21434236
